WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.680 --> 00:00:04.730
&gt;&gt; From the Library of
Congress in Washington DC.

00:00:06.510 --> 00:00:32.990
[Music]

00:00:32.990 --> 00:00:34.930
&gt;&gt; HELENA ZINKHAM: The
Library of Congress is home

00:00:34.930 --> 00:00:37.180
to the Rosa Parks Collection,

00:00:37.180 --> 00:00:42.020
on loan from the Howard G.
Buffett Foundation for 10 years.

00:00:42.020 --> 00:00:47.590
Mr. Buffett decided to purchase
this special material in 2014,

00:00:47.590 --> 00:00:51.300 position:56%
when he learned that it was
languishing in an auction warehouse.

00:00:51.300 --> 00:00:54.770
He wanted to bring these rare
items back into public view

00:00:54.770 --> 00:00:58.060
and ensure their preservation.

00:00:58.060 --> 00:01:02.040
Rosa Parks was a seminal figure
of the Civil Rights Movement.

00:01:02.040 --> 00:01:06.360
Her collection reveals how deeply
she believed in a moral imperative

00:01:06.360 --> 00:01:11.020
to oppose discrimination and
the denial of individual rights.

00:01:11.020 --> 00:01:14.420
That belief most famously
resulted in her decision

00:01:14.420 --> 00:01:20.340 position:56%
to challenge the bus segregation
laws in Montgomery, Alabama in 1955.

00:01:20.340 --> 00:01:23.620
But, her autobiographical
writings in this collection,

00:01:23.620 --> 00:01:26.080
they reveal numerous
times in her life

00:01:26.080 --> 00:01:30.680
when that conviction
motivated her to act.

00:01:30.680 --> 00:01:34.880
The collection documents many
aspects of her private life as well

00:01:34.880 --> 00:01:39.840
as her public work on behalf of
civil rights for African Americans.

00:01:39.840 --> 00:01:42.370 position:56%
While the 7,500 manuscript documents

00:01:42.370 --> 00:01:49.690
and the 2,500 photographs span
140 years, the content focuses

00:01:49.690 --> 00:01:54.510
on the decades of the
1950s through the 1990s.

00:01:54.510 --> 00:01:59.360
This includes Mrs. Parks' own
writings, letters from presidents,

00:01:59.360 --> 00:02:03.800
her Congressional Gold Medal, her
Presidential Medal of Freedom,

00:02:03.800 --> 00:02:07.320
and wonderful hand-drawn
cards of appreciation

00:02:07.320 --> 00:02:10.490
from scores of school children.

00:02:10.490 --> 00:02:13.330
What follows now, are
highlights from the collection

00:02:13.330 --> 00:02:17.850
and a look behind the scenes at how
our team of experts in cataloging,

00:02:17.850 --> 00:02:22.920
preservation, digitization,
exhibition, and teacher training,

00:02:22.920 --> 00:02:24.710
how they are all making this legacy

00:02:24.710 --> 00:02:28.710
of Rosa Parks available
to the world.

00:02:28.710 --> 00:02:32.100
We are deeply honored to have
been selected as the steward

00:02:32.100 --> 00:02:34.640
of the Rosa Parks Collection.

00:02:34.640 --> 00:02:39.510
&gt;&gt; HOWARD BUFFETT: I think
it's so important for us

00:02:39.510 --> 00:02:43.720
to remember the iconic
figures that changed our lives

00:02:43.720 --> 00:02:47.100
and that gave us what we have
and preserved what we have.

00:02:47.100 --> 00:02:53.570 position:56%
And so, an African-American woman in
the 1950s to do what Rosa Parks did,

00:02:53.570 --> 00:02:56.720
showed how much difference
one person can make.

00:02:56.720 --> 00:02:59.230
It's important for our
children to see that

00:02:59.230 --> 00:03:02.200
and to really embrace
it and understand it.

00:03:02.200 --> 00:03:05.450
Without getting this collection
out of the boxes and out

00:03:05.450 --> 00:03:08.530 position:56%
of the warehouse and in front of
people, that wasn't going to happen.

00:03:08.530 --> 00:03:12.880
And so, I thought we should, make
sure that this was in a place

00:03:12.880 --> 00:03:16.930
where millions of people can see it
and benefit from it and, obviously,

00:03:16.930 --> 00:03:20.770
the Library of Congress, there's
no place better than this facility

00:03:20.770 --> 00:03:23.240
and this team to do that.

00:03:23.240 --> 00:03:25.620
&gt;&gt; MARICIA BATTLE: We have a
very large collection that deals

00:03:25.620 --> 00:03:30.840
with civil rights and so it was
sort of a fulfillment of a dream

00:03:30.840 --> 00:03:34.500
to have the person who
they considered the mother

00:03:34.500 --> 00:03:39.680
of the Civil Rights Movement,
come into the collections.

00:03:39.680 --> 00:03:43.620
&gt;&gt; ADRIENNE CANNON: The Rosa Parks
Collection will illuminate other

00:03:43.620 --> 00:03:49.620
facets of her life, her family
life, her Christian faith

00:03:49.620 --> 00:03:55.400
and spirituality, her activism
post Montgomery bus boycott,

00:03:55.400 --> 00:04:00.800
and it will also shed additional
light on some of the details

00:04:00.800 --> 00:04:03.390
of the Montgomery bus boycott.

00:04:03.390 --> 00:04:06.110
&gt;&gt; MARICIA BATTLE: Most
people have the perception

00:04:06.110 --> 00:04:09.560
that Rosa Parks was
the lady who wore pink,

00:04:09.560 --> 00:04:15.380
the lady who always had a beautiful
purse, a beautiful hat on her head,

00:04:15.380 --> 00:04:19.970
and she was this quiet voice
that sort of spoke to you.

00:04:19.970 --> 00:04:23.450
But, I think one of the things
they'll realize after looking at

00:04:23.450 --> 00:04:25.790
and viewing this collection,

00:04:25.790 --> 00:04:29.050
is that she was a lion
underneath all of that.

00:04:29.050 --> 00:04:33.970
She had a way of softly drawing
you in and then sort of hitting you

00:04:33.970 --> 00:04:37.420
with the facts just
square between the eyes.

00:04:37.420 --> 00:04:39.400
And I think they'll be surprised.

00:04:39.400 --> 00:04:43.310
&gt;&gt; MEG MCALEER: Every
collection tells a story,

00:04:43.310 --> 00:04:45.500
well actually many stories.

00:04:45.500 --> 00:04:48.810
And the first thing I do when I
approach a collection is to try

00:04:48.810 --> 00:04:50.830
to discover what those stories are.

00:04:50.830 --> 00:04:53.820
And I do this by assessing
the scope of a collection

00:04:53.820 --> 00:04:55.520
and the relationship
between the parts.

00:04:55.520 --> 00:05:00.660
The collection came to us
stored in these cartons.

00:05:00.660 --> 00:05:06.810 position:56%
And in the cartons, papers were
grouped together in large envelopes.

00:05:06.810 --> 00:05:09.790
I've completed my initial
survey and I came

00:05:09.790 --> 00:05:13.770
up with broad categories
to arrange the papers.

00:05:13.770 --> 00:05:18.250
For instance, I have a category
of family correspondence.

00:05:18.250 --> 00:05:22.470 position:56%
This is the largest cache of letters
actually written by Rosa Parks

00:05:22.470 --> 00:05:25.260
in the collection and
they're very revealing.

00:05:25.260 --> 00:05:28.540
One that moves me in
particular is a letter she wrote

00:05:28.540 --> 00:05:30.490
to someone she addresses
as, Dear friend.

00:05:30.490 --> 00:05:32.670
I don't know who the person is.

00:05:32.670 --> 00:05:35.390
It's written on Montgomery
Fair stationary.

00:05:35.390 --> 00:05:38.530
She was employed at Montgomery Fair
at the time she refused to give

00:05:38.530 --> 00:05:42.460
up her seat on the bus
on December 1, 1955.

00:05:42.460 --> 00:05:46.770 position:56%
In this letter, she tries to set
what happened to her on December 1st

00:05:46.770 --> 00:05:50.140
in a broader context
of the Jim Crow South.

00:05:50.140 --> 00:05:53.560
She explains that segregation
is complete

00:05:53.560 --> 00:05:56.870
and a solid pattern-
it is the way we live.

00:05:56.870 --> 00:06:03.080
And then she goes on to describe
the experiences of people on buses,

00:06:03.080 --> 00:06:08.270 position:56%
having to go to segregated public
schools, churches, public libraries.

00:06:08.270 --> 00:06:12.250
And then also what it was like
to work at Montgomery Fair

00:06:12.250 --> 00:06:16.760
where she could not use the
restrooms used by white employees

00:06:16.760 --> 00:06:19.850
or the employee lounges and
she was not allowed to sit

00:06:19.850 --> 00:06:22.460
at the counter and have her lunch.

00:06:22.460 --> 00:06:26.250
But, at the end of the letter,
she closes with something

00:06:26.250 --> 00:06:28.420
that indicates the
gravity of the situation,

00:06:28.420 --> 00:06:34.160
that goes beyond the indignities of
the daily slaps of discrimination.

00:06:34.160 --> 00:06:37.530
She ends the letter by asking
if this person had heard

00:06:37.530 --> 00:06:42.640
about the lynch murder of Emmett
Till, the 14 year old teenager

00:06:42.640 --> 00:06:48.390 position:56%
from Chicago who was visiting family
in Mississippi in August, 1955,

00:06:48.390 --> 00:06:51.550
when he allegedly flirted
with a married white woman.

00:06:51.550 --> 00:06:54.910
And for this, he was
brutally murdered.

00:06:54.910 --> 00:06:59.040
She later tells Till's
mother that at that moment

00:06:59.040 --> 00:07:03.640 position:56%
when she was deciding whether to get
up from her seat on that bus or not,

00:07:03.640 --> 00:07:06.820
she thought about her son,
she thought about Emmett Till.

00:07:06.820 --> 00:07:10.930
&gt;&gt; ANITA PEEK: On the day that
she was arrested, she was sitting

00:07:10.930 --> 00:07:15.750
where she was supposed to
sit in the colored section.

00:07:15.750 --> 00:07:21.150
But, at that time, they used to
move the sign if they chose to.

00:07:21.150 --> 00:07:27.310
And the back of the bus was already
crowded so she didn't have to get

00:07:27.310 --> 00:07:34.330
up if there was no more seats
further back in the bus.

00:07:34.330 --> 00:07:39.260
And when the bus driver asked
for the four people to stand,

00:07:39.260 --> 00:07:41.780
none of them stood originally.

00:07:41.780 --> 00:07:44.280
But after he threatened jail,

00:07:44.280 --> 00:07:46.730
the other three got up,
but she kept sitting.

00:07:46.730 --> 00:07:50.580
&gt;&gt; ADRIENNE CANNON:
Rosa Parks' arrest

00:07:50.580 --> 00:07:54.520
for refusing a bus driver's
order to surrender her seat

00:07:54.520 --> 00:07:59.060
to a white passenger, happened
on December the 1st, 1955.

00:07:59.060 --> 00:08:01.990
There was no media present.

00:08:01.990 --> 00:08:04.820
There were no reporters
or photographers

00:08:04.820 --> 00:08:08.120 position:56%
to take photographs of the incident.

00:08:08.120 --> 00:08:12.160
The photograph that
is known worldwide

00:08:12.160 --> 00:08:16.060
that shows Rosa Parks
sitting on the bus

00:08:16.060 --> 00:08:20.660
with a white man sitting behind
her, was taken a year later

00:08:20.660 --> 00:08:25.730
on December 21st, 1956, the
first day that the buses

00:08:25.730 --> 00:08:29.250
in Montgomery, Alabama
were integrated.

00:08:29.250 --> 00:08:33.160
A month after the Montgomery
bus boycott began,

00:08:33.160 --> 00:08:38.460
Rosa Parks lost her 25 dollar a
week job as an assistant tailor

00:08:38.460 --> 00:08:40.820
at the Montgomery Fair
department store

00:08:40.820 --> 00:08:43.830
when it closed its tailor shop.

00:08:43.830 --> 00:08:48.560
Her husband, Raymond was
forced to resign his job

00:08:48.560 --> 00:08:54.950
at a private barber's concession
in Maxwell Field Air Force Base.

00:08:54.950 --> 00:09:01.440
In 1957, Rosa, Raymond, and her
mother, Leona, moved to Detroit

00:09:01.440 --> 00:09:04.260
to join her brother, Sylvester.

00:09:04.260 --> 00:09:06.720
She worked for 8 years

00:09:06.720 --> 00:09:12.180
as a seamstress before
becoming an office receptionist

00:09:12.180 --> 00:09:14.240
and administrative assistant

00:09:14.240 --> 00:09:19.910
for newly-elected Congressman,
John Conyers in 1965.

00:09:19.910 --> 00:09:26.780
And she served as his liaison with
the black community in Detroit.

00:09:26.780 --> 00:09:31.040
She kept abreast of all community
activities, attended rallies,

00:09:31.040 --> 00:09:36.520
and she particularly dealt with his
constituents' needs with concerns

00:09:36.520 --> 00:09:42.080
about welfare benefits, social
security, and job discrimination.

00:09:42.080 --> 00:09:44.440
&gt;&gt; MARICIA BATTLE: The
relationship that Mrs. Parks had

00:09:44.440 --> 00:09:50.400
with John Conyers was a very close
and kind one, as you can tell

00:09:50.400 --> 00:09:54.040
from this photo that
Conyers dedicated to her.

00:09:54.040 --> 00:09:58.660 position:56%
And it's signed, "to the mother of
the Civil Rights Movement, with love

00:09:58.660 --> 00:10:05.080
and thanks, John Conyers,
July 22, 1985."

00:10:05.080 --> 00:10:11.190 position:56%
One of the other pieces that we find
is this image of both Rosa Parks

00:10:11.190 --> 00:10:13.520
and Conyers protesting in front

00:10:13.520 --> 00:10:16.670
of the General Motors
warehouse or factory.

00:10:16.670 --> 00:10:20.970 position:56%
Protesting the closing, because so
many African Americans worked there,

00:10:20.970 --> 00:10:25.350
they thought this was unfair for
this particular plant to close.

00:10:25.350 --> 00:10:30.960
&gt;&gt; JOHN CONYERS: One day she came
to me and said, "Congressman,

00:10:30.960 --> 00:10:35.370
I'd like to ask for
a pay reduction."

00:10:35.370 --> 00:10:38.670
I said, "I beg your pardon?"

00:10:38.670 --> 00:10:42.960 position:56%
Nobody's ever asked for that before.

00:10:42.960 --> 00:10:46.810
Nobody's ever asked for
it since [laughter].

00:10:46.810 --> 00:10:50.990
And she said, "Well, you know,
you let me go so many places here

00:10:50.990 --> 00:10:53.530
in the country and even overseas."

00:10:53.530 --> 00:11:00.890
And I said, "Mrs. Parks, you
honor me by coming to my office

00:11:00.890 --> 00:11:04.860
and having worked with
me for so long."

00:11:04.860 --> 00:11:13.090
And it was no secret that more
people came to see Rosa Parks

00:11:13.090 --> 00:11:16.510
in my office than came to see me!

00:11:16.510 --> 00:11:24.070
[Music]

00:11:24.070 --> 00:11:25.690
&gt;&gt; MARY MUNDY: Preparing
collections for scholars

00:11:25.690 --> 00:11:28.800
to use involves a lot
of different activities.

00:11:28.800 --> 00:11:32.110
One of the first things I
do is survey the materials,

00:11:32.110 --> 00:11:34.200
get familiar with the
subject content

00:11:34.200 --> 00:11:37.200
and formats represented
in the collection.

00:11:37.200 --> 00:11:40.010
Then the next thing I
do is always look to see

00:11:40.010 --> 00:11:42.040
if the collection is organized.

00:11:42.040 --> 00:11:47.670
If there's a logical organization,
I want to keep that organization.

00:11:47.670 --> 00:11:50.520
If the collection lacks
any organization I'll need

00:11:50.520 --> 00:11:54.240
to impose an order that's
conducive to research.

00:11:54.240 --> 00:11:58.460
Next, formats with special
storage requirements are separated

00:11:58.460 --> 00:11:59.760
from the rest of the material.

00:11:59.760 --> 00:12:02.970
For instance, photographic
negatives need to be stored

00:12:02.970 --> 00:12:06.500
at cold temperatures for
preservation purposes.

00:12:06.500 --> 00:12:10.960
Large objects and fragile
items need to be stored flat

00:12:10.960 --> 00:12:15.400
in special boxes fit to their size.

00:12:15.400 --> 00:12:17.500
Additional work involves
placing items

00:12:17.500 --> 00:12:20.720
in containers, folders and sleeves.

00:12:20.720 --> 00:12:24.180
And every object has to be numbered

00:12:24.180 --> 00:12:26.720
with the collection
storage information

00:12:26.720 --> 00:12:30.070
so they can be easily
identified on the shelf.

00:12:30.070 --> 00:12:34.450
And items pulled can
be refiled after use.

00:12:34.450 --> 00:12:37.380
The final step involves describing
the collection in the form

00:12:37.380 --> 00:12:40.190
of a catalog record with
subject headings and lots

00:12:40.190 --> 00:12:43.690
of other access points so
scholars can find the material

00:12:43.690 --> 00:12:46.470
in our online catalog.

00:12:46.470 --> 00:12:49.510
All of these pictures really
reflect her lifelong commitment

00:12:49.510 --> 00:12:54.600
to civil rights, her work with
youth and her dedication to family.

00:12:54.600 --> 00:12:56.990
This is a very early photograph

00:12:56.990 --> 00:12:59.960
of her husband Raymond
Parks and his sister.

00:12:59.960 --> 00:13:04.260
This is unique in the sense that
it's mounted on a metal frame

00:13:04.260 --> 00:13:08.100
that is decorated with
a landscape scene.

00:13:08.100 --> 00:13:12.700
Rosa Parks had a lifelong interest
in helping youth and educating them

00:13:12.700 --> 00:13:14.520
about African American history.

00:13:14.520 --> 00:13:18.010
She started working with youth
actually in the late '40s

00:13:18.010 --> 00:13:20.520
with the NAACP youth council.

00:13:20.520 --> 00:13:24.550
This piece represents the impact
that Rosa Parks had on children.

00:13:24.550 --> 00:13:28.520
And it's a greeting card actually
from a group of school children

00:13:28.520 --> 00:13:31.560 position:56%
that was sent to her in 1998 and one

00:13:31.560 --> 00:13:33.560
of the largest greeting
cards we have

00:13:33.560 --> 00:13:36.950
in the collection from
school children.

00:13:36.950 --> 00:13:42.670
&gt;&gt; ADRIENNE CANNON: In 1987 she
co-founded with Elaine Steele,

00:13:42.670 --> 00:13:48.950 position:56%
the Rosa and Raymond Parks Institute
for Self Development as a tribute

00:13:48.950 --> 00:13:56.060
to her late husband, Raymond
who passed away in 1977.

00:13:56.060 --> 00:14:01.690
The purpose of the
institute was to motivate

00:14:01.690 --> 00:14:08.420
and direct the average youth
not targeted by other programs,

00:14:08.420 --> 00:14:12.670
towards achieving their
highest potential.

00:14:12.670 --> 00:14:16.450
&gt;&gt; MARICIA BATTLE: So, her
legacy is to instill in children,

00:14:16.450 --> 00:14:19.250
no matter how small your beginning,

00:14:19.250 --> 00:14:21.680
there's no end to what
you can achieve.

00:14:21.680 --> 00:14:26.040
So, here are photos of Rosa Parks

00:14:26.040 --> 00:14:30.250
at the John Freeman Walls
historic site in Canada.

00:14:30.250 --> 00:14:33.560
She's surrounded by children.

00:14:33.560 --> 00:14:37.340
One of the things that she
did with the institute,

00:14:37.340 --> 00:14:41.530
is they have a Pathways to
Freedom, where they take children

00:14:41.530 --> 00:14:45.480
onto different sites of
the Underground Railroad,

00:14:45.480 --> 00:14:49.210
and the Walls site is thought
to be one of the last sites

00:14:49.210 --> 00:14:51.890
on that Underground Railroad.

00:14:51.890 --> 00:14:57.290
Here we have, in Detroit, in
the 90's, a camp, a day camp,

00:14:57.290 --> 00:15:00.100
again, surrounded by children.

00:15:00.100 --> 00:15:02.340
She and Raymond did
not have any children,

00:15:02.340 --> 00:15:06.460
but her brother, Sylvester, had 13.

00:15:06.460 --> 00:15:09.250
&gt;&gt; ELAINE STEELE: When
children came into her midst,

00:15:09.250 --> 00:15:13.480
there was a wonderful smile
that came on her face.

00:15:13.480 --> 00:15:19.560
Didn't matter how young they were,
you know, up into their teen years.

00:15:19.560 --> 00:15:22.090
And if they were interested
in learning,

00:15:22.090 --> 00:15:25.510
she was just endeared to them more.

