and she would say, "Ms.
Parks you needed to have

00:32:15.840 --> 00:32:17.140
that medal a long time ago!"

00:32:17.140 --> 00:32:20.030
And she would just laugh at her,
she thought she was really funny.

00:32:20.030 --> 00:32:21.670
Every time I look at
the medal and think

00:32:21.670 --> 00:32:24.180
about the medal, I
think about that day.

00:32:24.180 --> 00:32:28.430
&gt;&gt; ANITA PEEK: She always seemed
to be surprised that people thought

00:32:28.430 --> 00:32:32.160
that what she did was so important.

00:32:32.160 --> 00:32:36.090
She felt that she made
a decision that day

00:32:36.090 --> 00:32:40.570
that no matter whether she lived
or died, that it was important

00:32:40.570 --> 00:32:45.230
to stop giving in when you
were doing the right thing.

00:32:45.230 --> 00:32:49.570
She really believed
in right and wrong.

00:32:49.570 --> 00:32:53.070
&gt;&gt; HOWARD BUFFETT: Rosa
Parks was all about freedom

00:32:53.070 --> 00:32:56.680
and you're sitting here in
Washington, DC and this is

00:32:56.680 --> 00:32:59.050
where our freedom is preserved.

00:32:59.050 --> 00:33:03.700
And so I think that to have
this collection sitting here

00:33:03.700 --> 00:33:09.830
in our capital is exactly
where it should be.

